The assignment is the Dam Rehabilitation and Improvement Project (DRIP) for the Central Water Commission in India, coordinated from the Project Director’s office in New Delhi [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:3](chunkref://3). Its objective is to develop and implement a comprehensive, web‑based management system and associated templates that capture technical, environmental, social and financial data for each dam, support site inspections, prioritize rehabilitation work, and provide technical, managerial and procurement assistance to the State Project Management Units (SPMUs) [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:20](chunkref://24). The work also includes detailed investigations for complex dams, preparation of environmental assessments and management plans, and the production of asset‑management plans to justify O&M budgeting [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:20](chunkref://24).

**Key deliverables** (as listed in the ToR) include:  
- A standard project‑template form and a customized web‑based MIS (the “DHARMA” software) [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:37](chunkref://62);  
- Quarterly and annual financial reports, interim unaudited financial reports, and compilation of audit reports [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:37](chunkref://62);  
- Project‑specific reports such as “Project Rehabilitation Report” for each dam, mid‑term and final implementation‑completion reports, and DRIP bulletins [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:37](chunkref://62);  
- Revised and new dam‑safety guidelines, a Dam Design Review Manual, and a Document Management & Dissemination System [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:37](chunkref://62);  
- System Requirement Studies (SRS) and the fully developed DHARMA software [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:37](chunkref://62);  
- Training calendars for capacity‑building programmes [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:37](chunkref://62).

**Specialness & potential difficulties** – The project deals with a large number of heterogeneous dams across India, some of which are “complicated or where major issues are involved,” requiring detailed site inspections, environmental assessments, and risk‑mitigation planning [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:20](chunkref://24). The need to integrate technical, environmental, social, financial and procurement data into a single MIS adds complexity.

**Innovative solutions** – The consultancy must design and customize software (including off‑the‑shelf add‑on components) and develop new guidelines and manuals, indicating a requirement for innovative, technology‑driven solutions [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:38](chunkref://66); [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:38](chunkref://65).

**Interdisciplinary expertise** – The scope spans dam engineering, environmental and social impact assessment, financial management, procurement, and information‑technology development, thus demanding expertise from multiple disciplines [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:20](chunkref://24).

**Software / tools / proprietary methodologies** – The tenderer is required to deliver the web‑based MIS, the DHARMA software, customized financial‑reporting tools, and associated documentation. All intellectual and commercial rights on these deliverables will vest with the CWC, and any off‑the‑shelf software licences must be held in CWC’s name [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:38](chunkref://65); [Tendernotice_1.pdf, p:38](chunkref://66). Hence, the bidder must provide the software, tools, and any proprietary methodologies as part of the contract.
